Analyze Injected Processes & Malicious DLLs
Learning Objectives
By completing this lab, you will:

Detect process injection techniques using memory forensics
Extract and analyze malicious DLLs from memory dumps
Investigate malware interactions with legitimate system processes
Use open-source tools for advanced memory analysis
Prerequisites
Basic understanding of Linux command line
Familiarity with process concepts and memory management
Knowledge of Windows PE file structure (helpful but not required)
Understanding of malware analysis fundamentals
Lab Environment
Al Nafi provides Linux-based cloud machines for this lab. Simply click Start Lab to access your dedicated environment. The provided Linux machine is bare metal with no pre-installed tools, so you will install all required tools during the lab.

Task 1: Set Up Analysis Environment and Obtain Memory Dump
Subtask 1.1: Install Required Tools
# Update system packages
sudo apt update && sudo apt upgrade -y

# Install Python and pip
sudo apt install python3 python3-pip git wget unzip -y

# Install Volatility 3 (latest memory forensics framework)
pip3 install volatility3

# Install additional analysis tools
sudo apt install hexdump binutils file -y

# Verify Volatility installation
vol3 --help
Subtask 1.2: Download Sample Memory Dump
# Create working directory
mkdir ~/memory_analysis && cd ~/memory_analysis

# Download a sample Windows memory dump with process injection
wget https://github.com/volatilityfoundation/volatility/raw/master/contrib/plugins/malware/samples/zeus.vmem -O infected_memory.vmem

# If the above fails, create a simulated environment
# Download alternative sample
wget https://www.memoryanalysis.net/samples/stuxnet.vmem -O infected_memory.vmem

# Verify file download
ls -lh infected_memory.vmem
file infected_memory.vmem
Task 2: Analyze Memory Dump for Injected Processes
Subtask 2.1: Identify System Information and Processes
# Determine Windows version and build
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.info

# List all running processes
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.pslist > process_list.txt

# Display process tree to identify parent-child relationships
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.pstree

# Look for suspicious processes
cat process_list.txt | grep -E "(svchost|explorer|winlogon|csrss)"
Subtask 2.2: Detect Process Hollowing and Injection
# Check for process hollowing (legitimate process with malicious code)
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.malfind

# Identify processes with unusual memory characteristics
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.memmap --pid [SUSPICIOUS_PID]

# Scan for injected code patterns
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.vadinfo --pid [SUSPICIOUS_PID]

# Look for processes with mismatched executable paths
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.dlllist --pid [SUSPICIOUS_PID]
Subtask 2.3: Analyze Suspicious Process Memory
# Dump suspicious process memory for analysis
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.memmap --pid [SUSPICIOUS_PID] --dump

# Extract process executable
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.procdump --pid [SUSPICIOUS_PID]

# Analyze dumped memory regions
hexdump -C pid.[SUSPICIOUS_PID].dmp | head -50

# Search for suspicious strings in memory
strings pid.[SUSPICIOUS_PID].dmp | grep -E "(http|ftp|\.exe|\.dll)" | head -20
Task 3: Extract and Review Malicious DLLs
Subtask 3.1: Identify Loaded DLLs
# List all DLLs loaded by suspicious processes
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.dlllist --pid [SUSPICIOUS_PID] > dll_list.txt

# Look for unsigned or suspicious DLLs
cat dll_list.txt | grep -v "C:\\Windows\\System32"

# Check for DLLs loaded from unusual locations
cat dll_list.txt | grep -E "(Temp|AppData|Users)"
Subtask 3.2: Extract Malicious DLLs
# Dump specific DLL from memory
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.dlldump --pid [SUSPICIOUS_PID] --base [DLL_BASE_ADDRESS]

# Extract all DLLs from suspicious process
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.dlldump --pid [SUSPICIOUS_PID]

# List extracted DLL files
ls -la *.dll

# Analyze DLL file properties
for dll in *.dll; do
    echo "=== Analyzing $dll ==="
    file "$dll"
    strings "$dll" | head -10
    echo ""
done
Subtask 3.3: Analyze DLL Injection Techniques
# Check for reflective DLL loading
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.handles --pid [SUSPICIOUS_PID] | grep -i "section"

# Look for manual DLL mapping evidence
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.vadinfo --pid [SUSPICIOUS_PID] | grep -E "(PAGE_EXECUTE|PRIVATE)"

# Search for DLL injection artifacts
strings infected_memory.vmem | grep -E "(LoadLibrary|GetProcAddress|VirtualAlloc)" | head -10
Task 4: Investigate Malware Interactions with System Processes
Subtask 4.1: Analyze Network Connections
# Extract network connections from memory
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.netstat

# Look for suspicious network activity
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.netscan | grep -E "(ESTABLISHED|LISTENING)"

# Check for DNS queries
strings infected_memory.vmem | grep -E "([a-zA-Z0-9-]+\.)+[a-zA-Z]{2,}" | sort | uniq | head -20
Subtask 4.2: Examine Registry Modifications
# Extract registry hives
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.registry.hivelist

# Look for persistence mechanisms
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.registry.printkey --key "Software\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Run"

# Check for service installations
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.svcscan | grep -v "SYSTEM"
Subtask 4.3: Analyze File System Interactions
# List file handles for suspicious processes
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.handles --pid [SUSPICIOUS_PID] | grep "File"

# Extract suspicious files from memory
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.filescan | grep -E "(\.exe|\.dll|\.bat)" | head -20

# Dump specific files if found
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.dumpfiles --virtaddr [FILE_ADDRESS]
Subtask 4.4: Create Analysis Report
# Generate comprehensive analysis report
cat > analysis_report.txt << EOF
=== Memory Forensics Analysis Report ===

Date: $(date)
Memory Dump: infected_memory.vmem

SUSPICIOUS PROCESSES IDENTIFIED:
$(vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.pslist | grep -E "(unusual_process_name)")

INJECTED DLLS FOUND:
$(ls -la *.dll 2>/dev/null || echo "No DLLs extracted")

NETWORK CONNECTIONS:
$(vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.netstat 2>/dev/null | head -10)

PERSISTENCE MECHANISMS:
$(vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.registry.printkey --key "Software\\Microsoft\\Windows\\CurrentVersion\\Run" 2>/dev/null | head -5)

RECOMMENDATIONS:
- Quarantine identified malicious processes
- Remove persistence registry entries
- Block identified network communications
- Update antivirus signatures

EOF

# Display report
cat analysis_report.txt
Verification and Testing
Verify Analysis Results
# Confirm tools are working
echo "=== Tool Verification ==="
vol3 --version
python3 --version

# Verify extracted artifacts
echo "=== Extracted Files ==="
ls -la *.dmp *.dll 2>/dev/null || echo "No artifacts extracted"

# Check analysis outputs
echo "=== Analysis Files ==="
ls -la *.txt

# Validate memory dump integrity
echo "=== Memory Dump Info ==="
file infected_memory.vmem
Troubleshooting Common Issues
Issue: Volatility fails to recognize memory dump format

# Try different profile detection
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.info.Info
Issue: No suspicious processes found

# Use broader search criteria
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.malfind --pid ALL
Issue: DLL extraction fails

# Check available memory regions first
vol3 -f infected_memory.vmem windows.vadinfo --pid [PID]
Conclusion
In this lab, you successfully:

Set up a complete memory forensics environment using open-source tools
Identified process injection techniques through memory analysis
Extracted and analyzed malicious DLLs from infected processes
Investigated malware persistence mechanisms and system interactions
Created a comprehensive analysis report documenting findings
These skills are essential for incident response, malware analysis, and digital forensics roles. Memory forensics provides crucial insights into advanced threats that traditional file-based analysis might miss, making it a valuable technique for cybersecurity professionals investigating sophisticated attacks and APT activities.

The techniques learned here apply directly to real-world scenarios where malware uses process injection, DLL hijacking, and memory-resident attacks to evade detection while maintaining persistence on compromised systems.
